node.text: UPDATE: goldfish were returned! I was told these wouldn’t get large and when I brought them back I was told by another person that the first guy was wrong hahahaha. Thanks for the tips yall. Added some beneficial substrate for the plants and replaced them with a small scoop of tetras. A little experiment in propagation. I feed the fish, the fish shit out their butts and the roots are tickled with fecal joy and in return, so am I.

node.text:
I just wrapped up the custom crystallized commissions from February! And I already got these Crystal covered juicy boys ready for you! I’ve opened up preorders for the next several batches of crystallized cicadas on my site! There’s no limit to how many you can preorder and I even have a wholesale option for shops that want to carry my work! Click the “available work” tab on my site tylerthrasher.com you can also nab my sport hunting guide for free!
#tylerthrasher #crystallized #science #chemistry #cicada #curio #curiosity #crystals #gems #minerals

node.text:
A little family shot of some of my Monstera sports! Mostly comprised of the Thrasher sport. You can see the intense variety of leaves my sport puts out as well as the reward for propagating and taking cuttings. I lost a lot of plants during the move and pandemic depression but everything is slowly growing back and taking root, and I’m growing with them. 
#monsteramonday #variegated #variegation #monstera #houseplants

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Tyler Thrasher on July 18, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
A tiny jar of my lab grown opal. The recipe I’m using yields chunks of opal that diffract light into every color on the visible spectrum. At some angles the pieces look almost colorless/ white and with a tiny twist or rotation the pieces burst with color. This process requires that spheres of silica all line up just right to form a cubic lattice. It helps if a majority/ all of the spheres have similar diameter or at least diameters wide enough to break up light and reveal the “colors” that make up white light. This is in my dimly lit lab with no direct beams of light, you can scroll further down on my page to see microscopic images of pieces from the same recipe.
#science #opal #labgrown #chemistry

node.text:
Every now and then I’ll hear an occasional pop and sprinkling sound in my sunroom. I was drinking some coffee and a literal seed popped off of my face and noticed one of the oxalis growing in a pot decided it was time to launch its offspring! A lot of interesting designs and technology can be inspired by simply watching how nature operates. I set up a black backdrop and focused in with a macro lens attachment for my phone and flicked the seed pod with a toothpick. I did my best to keep it in focus but I didn’t want to hold it too closely with my fingers and risk missing the shot.
#plants #slomo #plantsinslowmotion #oxalis #nature #design #botany

node.text: One of several illustrations for @rewild and their initiative to find and rediscover previously thought extinct species. I was asked to illustrate around 10 different animals including the  Incilius periglenes, also known as the golden toad. This amphibian is native to the Eflin cloud forest, a high altitude environment rich with vibrant tropicals and epiphytes. The last sighting of this animal was on May 15, 1989. There is reason to believe that the Golden Toad could be rediscovered. #rewild #goldentoad #science #biology #conservation #scienceart #illustration
